column168: Driver was unloading product from tanker truck to receiving tank product fill at the station. While preparing to unload the second compartment on truck, driver failed to assure that the Betts valve was completely closed on truck header.  When driver proceeded to open the lid used to seal the header piping approximately 2 gallons of product released.  Driver had hit the truck compartment internal valve prematurely.  This action was not consistent with routine loading procedures.  Driver immediately closed the Betts valve after initial release.  Product was cleaned up with spill pads.
column169: Review of established driver procedures and continued awareness training.

column168: On 2/6/07, Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. was transporting a shipment containing capacitor voltage transformers (CCVTs) from its 10-day transfer facility in Port Washington, WI to a Veolia disposal facility located in Phoenix, AZ.  The CCVTs were oil filled and shipped to the TSDF classified as PCB material.  This initial classification was based on the PCB assumption requirements of 40 CFR 761 since actual concentration of PCB was not confirmed by testing.      During a roadside inspection, it was discovered that a CCVT was leaking a small amount of oil which was contained within the pan-lined trailer.  Upon further investigation, it was determined that the CCVT failed due to a crack in the ceramic portion of the unit.  The unit is approximately 8 feet long and is constructed of steel, copper and ceramics.  The spill was cleaned and the NRC was notified because the concentration of PCBs was unknown at the time.    Upon arrival at the TSDF, the data plate was retrieved from the CCVT, which shows that the unit was manufactured in 2000 and contained no PCB's.  This information was later confirmed by lab testing of the spilled material.  Lab data was not available to the shipper at the time the item was originally offered for transportation, so they took a conservative approach and shipped the item as PCB material until it could be confirmed by testing.  As such, the unit was described as a hazardous material on the shipping paper.  In addition, all activities up to the time where the concentration of PCBs could be confirmed, were conducted as though the oil was a hazardous material.  After confirming that the material did not contain regulated levels of PCBs, the NRC was contacted and the spill report was modified to note that an RQ release did not occur.
column169: Although Special Provision 81 allows PCB items to be shipped as is when specification packaging is impractical, Veolia ES Technical Solutions is conducting an evaluation of alternate methods of packaging and securing items which have a high percentage of ceramic.

column168: Truck was being loaded and no product would flow from the loading arm.  Driver entered warehouse and reset various switches to correct no flow condition.  Valve on loading arm was open.  When flow returned, product was pumping out of loading arm.  Loading arm was not in manhole on top of vehicle.  Product was pumping onto the concrete containment area around the loading rack.  By the time driver retured from warehouse, several hundrec gallons had been dispensed into containment area.  Local environmental cleanup firm was contacted to remove product from contamiment area.
column169: All loading arms will have valves which must be held open by loading personnell.  If no one is holding valve open, product will not flow.  Easier access to emergency shut off switchs not located on the loading rack.  Train all personell in location and operation of shut off switches.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT PRO# 945-982111 WAS A TOTE 225 GALLONS THAT WAS MOVED FROM ORIGIN FRESNO, CA ONTO TRAILER 313-1909 AND ARRIVED INTO KETTLEMAN CITY LEAKING. column169: A RECOMMENDATION FOR THE SHIPPER OF THIS TOTE IS TO USE A BETTER STRONG SEAL AND COUPLING AROUND THE VALVE SO THE IPACTS DURING TRANSIT DOES NOT MOVE OR LOOSEN UP THE COUPLING SO WE COULD PREVENT SPILLS LIKE THIS ONE.

column168: On February 10, 2007, the driver for Justin Davis Enterprises was off loading gasoline at a Sunoco station in Auburndale, Florida.  Suddenly the fuel vapor line began to leak.  Approximately 25 gallons of gasoline leaked onto the concrete surface at the station.  A cleanup crew was called to mitigate the fuel spill.  Once on site the ER Team applied granular sorbents to the free product.  This was then swept up and placed into a drum for disposal.   The driver believes that an air bubble must have delveloped in the fuel vapor line resulting in the leak.  The entire cleanup process took approximately 2 hours from the initial notice.

column168: Upon arrival at stop, delivery driver noticed a crack at top of tote.  It appeared to him that during the cold spell (sub zero temperatures) that the material froze and cracked the top of tote open.  It is difficult to estimate if anything was lost at all but since the tote was below the fill line it was appoximated that 10 gallons may have been lost.    A clean up company came out...material was placed in heated area and then transferred into drums.  All material was returned to shipper for reworking.
column169: Material should probably been held or shipped in a heated unit.  The subzero temperatures effected freight even though it was delivered within 24 hours.

column168: Freight damaged due to Improper loading. Freight assigned to pro 709169661 was loaded on skids three (3) across in the nose of trailer Gork-4440. These skids were tight up againist one another with zero visabillty between skids. The damage was discovered once the freight was pulled to the floor due to the fact that the damage was in the front right hand corner of the skid. When loaded the front right corner of the pallet scored the cartons, then pails, causing the spill. We found that both the stretch wrap and the cardboard of the box the shipment was packaged in were torn away from the nose of the trailer. This leads us to believe that the damage occurred during the loading rather than the unload process. Had this incident occurred while unloading the material listed above would have torn in the opposite direction. Once we discovered the spill we immediately notified our Safety Manager to inform him of the incident. The packages were torn open by the corner of a pallet when loaded. The packages had a one (1) by six (6) inch tear in them. The pails had dents/folds with a small tear in the metal, about a centimeter in diameter.    The duration of the release over twenty (20) hours, roughly the transit time Sante Fe Springs, CA to Renton WA.
column169: My suggestion would be for extra Space and Visiability training with all operators, with an emphasis on being aware of surroundings.

column169: The customer should verify the contents of a container prior to bill it out and shipping it to an ocean carrier.  There should be a 24 hour advance receipt of all hazardous cargo received at a marine termina.  This will allow for a better cargo stow and manifest planning.

column168: Transport driver was distracted in cab and veered left-of-center onto oncoming traffic shoulder while traveling around curve. Driver attempted to return to lane, but overcorrected steering causing transport to roll-over.  A passerby was quickly on the scene and reported the incident. Emergency and environmental crews immediately responded to the scene. Crude oil was released from the cargo tank's sidewall(2'split near a center baffle) due to overturn and asphalt surface abrasion during skid. Emergency environmental crews arrived on scene and diked free crude oil in drainage ditch and then recovered with vacuum truck.  A second transport was brought to scene to offload overturned transport. The contaminated soil was excavated and removed from the site.  After clean-closure, the site was then backfilled.
column169: Heighten empahsis on the dangers of in-cab distractions, multi-tasking while driving and keeping eyes on the road.  Also provide better training on best practices to return a truck on the road without overcorrection (Slow down or come to complete stop before returning to the road.

A van trailer containing a shipment of hazardous waste was enroute to a licensed waste management facility.  During the course of transportation, the driver made a routine comfort stop and discovered that product was dripping from the rear tailgate of the vehicle.  The driver immediately placed a containment device under the trailer, contacted his home dispatcher and the truck stop manager where the vehicle was parked.  In addition, the Ohio EPA was called and a verbal report was made.  Upon notification a response crew was dispatched and upon arrival on site discovered that approximatley 20 gallons of material had escaped from a crack that developed in the lower seam of a 55 gallon stell drum onto the floor of the van trailer and into the containment device set up under the trailer.  The response crew collected all spilled material and placed it, along with the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum for continuing transportation.  Prior to departure from the site that area was inspected and it was determined that all released material was cleaned and the truck was placed back into service.
column169: Prior to departure, the load was inspected and no visible sign of damage was identified during the loading process.  In order to prevent a recurrence, drivers willbe instructed to continue to inspect each container before it is accepted for transportation and to take appropriate actions should a damaged or suspect container be indentified.

Based on the report of the odor of paint thinner, the case was referred to the FAA. I spoke to SA in LAX. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers , emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The freight is being held pending abn FAA inspection.

column168: At approximately 11:15 am the car loader started filling railcar CPDX 202087 with asphalt which was located on spot #3 track 733.  He then tended to other duties by closing, tightening and sealing the dome lids on the two railcars located on the same track.  The loader then went to the bottom of the rack and installed the belly cap on the railcar sitting on spot #1.  At approximately 11:50 am he was approaching the railcar sitting on spot #2 and he heard loud popping noises coming from the railcar being loaded on spot #3.  He saw product “jumping” out of the dome of railcar CPDX 202087 and he ran to the pump shut off switch which is located under the rack near spot #1.  He then went on top of the rack and shut the valve to the loading arm.  The railcar continued to make “popping” noises.  When he was certain that it was safe to approach the dome lid of the railcar he looked inside the car and saw that the product level was exactly on the marker.
column169: Loading racks supervisor will reaffirm with the railcar loaders the need to pay close attention to the railcars that are filling, especially with hot or reactive products.    "Safety Stand-Down" meeting was conducted with the entire loading racks division on 2/16/07.

column168: At approx. 11:30 am a contractor with Martin Transport started transferring molten sulfur from his truck into railcar ITDX 5092.  The railcar loader assigned to assist the driver accessed the top of the railcar and opened the dome lid to check the railcar and verified that the flow had started.  The loader said it looked like 2 to 2.5 feet of the hose extended into the railcar.  After verifying that the flow had started, he descended the rack without closing the lid onto the transfer hose.  Both the truck driver and the loader stood at the back of the truck while the transfer occurred.  When the truck emptied, a surge of air caused the hose end to jump out of the railcar and spray sulfur onto the rack, ground and railcar.  The truck driver stated that the air pressure was the same as previous transfers and the only difference was the dome lid position.  The loader stated that he thought that the lid should have been in the open position and that he was not formally trained on the procedure.
column169: A safety stand down meeting was conducted the morning of 02/16/2007 with the Loading Racks Division and the Safety Department.    A device will be fabricated to prevent this reoccurrence.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Procedures
column168: ON FRIDAY, FEBRUARY, FEBRUARY 16TH AT 0956 HOURS, A CSX TRANSPORTATION BENNETT YARD CAR INSPECTOR OBSERVED TANK CAR DODX14224 (RESIDUE-LAST CONTAINED FUEL, AVIATION, TURBINE ENGINE) DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AREA.  CSX MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THEIR EMERGENCY ACTION PLAN, ISOLATED THE AREA, AND A TRAIN CREW MOVED THE TANK CAR OVER THE EXPEDITE TRACK FOR REPAIRS.  THE SHIPPER GOVERNMENT, WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE RELEASE.  CSX CONTRACTED HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CONTAINER.  ONCE ON SITE, HEPACO REPRESENTATIVES FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE FOLLOWING:  BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPEN (OPERATING HANDLE IN OPEN POSITION - NOT PINNED), BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET TORN.  AT 1330 HOURS, HEPACO REPLACED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET AND CAR WAS SECURED AND FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.    NARRI:  5(4+1+0)*(2+0)=50  CAUSE CODE=148

column168: CSXT HARZARDOUS MATERIALS RECEIVED A CALL REPORTING AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 37457 IN COLLIER YARD, PETERSBURG, VA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  HEPACO PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND DETERMINED THE EXTERNAL PRD WAS LEAKING VAPOR.  THE RAIL CAR WAS SCRUBBED DOWN TO 18 LBS PRESSURE.  ONCE THE PRESSURE WAS OFF THE CAR, NO FURTHER ODORS WERE DETECTED.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTRACTED THE CAR OWNER, WHO HIRED SPECIALIZED PROFESSIONAL SERVICES TO REPLACE THE VALVE AND TEST THE CAR PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.    CHEMTREC REPORT #02112007004    NARRI:  5(4+5+0)*(2+0)=90  CAUSE CODE=422

column168: A 10-15 GALOON DIESEL RELEASE THAT OCCURRED ON 02/06/07 AT 1201 HORSHOE PIKE, GUTHRIESVILLE, PA.  WAS DETERMINED TO BE CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR.  TWO DRIVERS WERE ASSIGNED TO PUMP OUT AN UST AT THE SPILL LOCATION.  COMPANY STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES REQUIRE ONE DRIVER TO OPERATE THE PUMP AND ONE DRIVER TO REMAIN ON TOP OF THE TANK TRAILER TO MONITOR THE PRODUCT FLOW INTO EACH COMPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER THAT WAS STATIONED ON TOP OF THE TRAILER FAILED TO REMAIN AT HIS POST AND THE COMPARTMENT WAS OVERFILLED CAUSING THE SPILL.    THE PENNSYLVANIA DEP WAS NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE AND SUNOCO, INC. (R&M) WAS ON THE SCENE DRUING THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY MULRY AND CRESSWELL ENVIRONMENTAL, INC.
column169: PUMP-OUT PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED WITH THE RESPONSIBLE DRIVER BY THE REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER.

column168: GATX 11383, LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BELL CAP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION’S RAIL YARD IN AVON, IN. THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE DRIP. CSXT’S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, AMERICAN REFINING GROUP, VIA CHEMTREC (REPORT# 02052007038). THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE DRIP. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE DRIP TO BE COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET BELL CAP. THEY ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BELL CAP BUT WERE ONLY ABLE TO SNUG IT UP. THE OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHT. THE CONTRACTOR OPENED AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE IN AN ATTEMPT TO RESEAT IT AND THEN LOOSENED THE BELL CAP TO ALLOW ENTRAINED PRODUCT TO DRAIN INTO A BUCKET. THE DRIP CONTINUED. THE BELL CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET PIPE AND BELL CAP WERE WRAPPED IN ABSORBENT PADS AND COVERED WITH A PLASTIC BAG TO CONTAIN THE DRIP. AMERICAN REFINING GROUP WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR. THEY CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, HERITAGE CRYSTAL CLEAN LLC, WHO AGREED TO ACCEPT THE CAR IN A LEAKING CONDITION TO OFFLOAD THE PRODUCT. AMERICAN REFINING OBTAINED AN FRA APPROVAL NUMBER (FRA07020040) TO PERMIT THE MOVE OF THE CAR TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING. THE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE CAR ON 02/09/07 TO CONFIRM AND VERIFY THAT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FORM THE CAR PRIOR TO TRANSPORT TO THE CONSIGNEE.     NARRI: 5(5+1+0)*(2+0)=60   Cause Code = 662

column168: Tankcar UTLX 12432 was reported leaking super phosphoric acid to the ground inside the railyard at Columbus, NE, Regional Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, inspected the car and advised that the release was a steady drip from around the bottom outlet valve and approximately five gallons of acid had been released. Was advised the release was caused by six loose mounting bolts where the valve attaches to the outlet saddle on the tankcar. Tightening the six bolts 1/2 a turn stopped the release. Sodium bicarbonate was used to neutralize the released acid and decontaminate the car.

column168: Manager of Yard Operations, reported and unknown amount of product was leaking from the bottom of tank car ETCX 22030, located at Yard 6, Track 203, Settegast Yard; Houston, TX. Upon receiving the call, Mgr.  responded and requested the   RMCC to make shipper notification via Chem-Trec.     Mgr. observed product dripping from the bottom of the car at a rate of   approximately one drop every second. Inspection of the car revealed the 3 inch liquid ball valve to be open 1/8 turn, and the liquid valve plug in position loose turn. Upon closing of the valve, and tightening of the plug, the car was secure from further leakage, and released to continue onto destination without further incident.     At 1821 hrs Mgr spoke to shipper personnel from Eastman Chemical advising them of the release and corrective actions taken. There were no reported injuries, drains or waterways impacted resulting from this release. No clean-up was required as product evaporated upon contact with the atmosphere.     Combination   Housing original seal #DOW 007907; replaced with UPRR CTS 0008794.

He advised he was on scene with the Tucson Fire Department, the total quantity of product released was about 20 gallons with a small amount pooling on the ground. He advised the release was stopped at 07:00 PM. He further advised the release was the result of a liquid line valve which was loose by three and one-half turns. Employee advised the valve was secured wrench tight and tankcar was released for normal transportation. He removed seal (SEALED 06061 64) from the valve cover lid. Reapplied seal EMG 006269 when completed.

column168: Our driver departed from the Harahan facility enroute to Sun Drilling Products at approximately 9:30AM. At approximately 10:00AM, while traveling on General DeGaulle Blvd., he was notified by a passing motorist that liquid was leaking from his trailer. He drove into an empty parking lot of an abandoned resuaurant. After inspecting the interior of the trailer, he determined that Sodium Hydroxide was leaking from a crack in the sidewall of an IBC. He then contacted his Facility Manager who began the required notification process at approximately 10:20AM. Oil Mop LLC, along with LA DEQ, arrived on-scene at approximately 11:15AM. Under the direction of LA DEQ, Oil Mop personnel proceeded to mitigate the immediate spill area. At the request of the New Orleans Police Dept., the Dept. of Transportation spread sand on a section of Interstate 10 East that had been closed due to the spill. This roadway was reopened at approximately 2:00PM. Decontamination of the truck, trailer and surrounding area was completed at 4:15PM. The damaged IBC was returned to our facility for inspection. We will continue to monitor IBC's during the Pre-Fill Inspection procedure.
column169: Continued monitoring of IBC's during the Pre-Fill Inspection procedure.

column168: Driver was pulling to customer location when he had to stop quickly due to a car pulling out in front of him.  He then proceeded to the unloading area where he opened up the trailer doors of Univar trailer 1933 and discovered that a strap had come loose resultling in two drums of caustic soda had fallen over.  One of the durms leaked approximately 30 gallons of product through a crack in the top with approximately 10 gallons leaking out of the doors onto the customer’s asphalt parking lot.  The employees at the customer location were informed of the incident and another Univar driver was dispatched to the customer location to assist with additional spill clean up supplies.  They doned the necessary PPE and placed the drum into an overpack, cleaned up the spilled material in the area.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. dispatched a 5000 gallon tank transporter to NPC Services, Inc. in order to load approximatley 3500 gallons of a flammable liquid being sent for disposal. Upon arrival, the driver positioned the tank on a contained loading pad and loading operations commenced. Upon conclusion of the loading operation, the driver and facility personnel inspected the vehicle and determined that a small leak had developed on the bottom barrel of the tank. A containment device was placed under the drip and an alternate tank transporter was mobilized to the site. Upon arrival, the contents on the leaking tank were transferrred to the secodnd transporter. This operation was done without incident and the shipment was released to the driver for transportation to the intended waste management facility. The tank transporter that was found to be leaking was laced out of service and is currently being evaluated for repairs though the estimate to repair the tank is $5000.00. PLease note that the cause of this leak is not believed to be attributed to the material loaded into the transporter. The tank in question was made of a material that was compatible with the flammable liquid being loaded.
column169: The tank in question was in normal service and had not experienced a leak prior to this event. Clean Harbors will continue to inspect it’s trailers and insure that the tanks are within the required inspection parameters and will place out of service any vehicle that shows evidence of damage and/or deterioration.

column168: BOBTAIL DRIVER, WAS DRIVING ON A VERY RURAL DIRT ROAD AND TURNING RIGHT ONTO A DIFFERENT ROAD THAT WAS ALSO RURAL AND NARROW.  THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT CUT BACK AT ABOUT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE, SO IT WAS NOT EASY FOR THE TRUCK TO MAKE THE TURN IN ONE MOTION. THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT ALSO WAS A DOWNHILL SLOPE. THE DRIVER COULD NOT NEGOTIATE THE TURN IN ONE MOTION, STOPPED AND ATTEMPTED TO BACK UP TO RE-ALIGN THE VEHICLE.  THE TRUCK DID NOT HAVE ENOUGH TRACTION TO BACK UP THE HILL.  THE DRIVER GOT OUT AND CLEARED THE SNOW AWAY FROM THE EDGE OF THE ROAD SO HE COULD SEE IT. HE THOUGHT HE HAD ENOUGH FIRM GROUND TO CONTINUE HIS TURN, BUT OBVIOUSLY HE DID NOT. THE TRUCK ROLLED DOWN THE BANK ABOUT 25-30 FEET COMING TO REST ON ITS DRIVERS SIDE. THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.
column169: THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED TWICE IMMEDIATELY BEFORE IT HAPPENED IF THE DRIVER HAD USED BETTER JUDGEMENT.  1.  HE SHOULD NOT HAVE ATTEMPTED TO MAKE SHARP TURN AS HE DID.  IT WOULD HAVE BEEN BETTER TO TAKE THE TURN TO THE LEFT, TURN AROUND IN A SAFE PLACE AND COME BACK.  2. HE HAD THE VEHICLE STOPPED ON THE GOOD PART OF THE ROAD AND MADE A DECISION TO PROCEED.  HE COULD HAVE CALLED FOR A TOW TRUCK TO PULL HIM BACKWARDS THE LITTLE THAT HE NEEDED TO SAFELY COMPLETE THE TURN.    THE GROUND RAILS ON THIS ROAD END BEFORE THE INTERSECTION ALSO.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at the customer facility, a valve was damaged, which resulted in the release of approximately 75 gallons of free liquid.  MG Waldbaun contained the free liquid with the application of absorbent material to the free liquid.  Environmental Solutions, Inc. of Wakefield, Nebraska was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, Environmental Solutions, Inc. detected free product and rinse water along the affected concrete lot.  There were no storm drains, waterways, or surface soils affected by the release.  Environmental Solutions, Inc. proceeded to apply absorbent material and floor dry to the affected area, and containerized the spent absorbent material, floor dry, and contaminated snow into eight (8) 55-gallon recovery drums.  The site was secured, pending completion of cleanup during daylight hours on the following day.  Environmental Solutions, Inc. returned to the site on 2/15 to complete the cleanup.  An additional six (6) 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material were generated.  Fourteen (14) 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material and floor dry were transported to Waste Express, Inc. in Kansas City, Missouri for incineration.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release appears to be related to damage to the valve during offloading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Ecolab, Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: A Washington state hazardous material inspector reported BNSF 880171 dripping residue product from the bottom outlet in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was dispatched from nearby Pasco, WA to inspect and secure BNSF 880171. The responder reported that the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) operating rod was n a slightly open position by 1/8 turn. Responder closed the TOBOV. The TOBOV operating rod’s packing gland nut appeared tight and the rod’s packing material was sufficient. Inspection of the bottom outlet revealed 3 of 6 flange bolt studs were damaged and broken which allowed residue diesel fuel to escape from around the flange area. Dripping stopped after the TOBOV was closed and secured. BNSF environmental contractors excavated impacted soil and placed it inside two 55 gallon recovery drums for appropriate future disposal. Ground remediation was completed by 1630 hrs. PST, 2/14/07. BNSF 880171 was redirected to a qualified repair facility at Finley, WA for repairs to the bottom outlet flange connection.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 62623 leaking product from the top of this tank car during normal switching activities in the railyard. Movement was stopped and GATX 62623 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical responder neutralized and wiped spillage on the side shell and around the fill hole cover area. No ground impact was evident. Shipper responders reported that one of the three fill hole securement bolts was not tool tight. Responders checked the product outage level and it was deemed appropriate. Responders then resecured the fill hole cover and tool tightened all securement bolts. Afterwards, GATX 62623 was moved in the railyard and no further product release was observed, GATX 62623 was then released to proceed to its destination. Response was concluded by 1130 hrs. CST, 2/17/07.

column168: A roll-by inspection of a departing BNSF train from the Temple railyard revealed entrained PSPX 29379 with product dampness at the bottom outlet area. The train was stopped on the main track and a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was dispatched from Temple to investigate. The responder reported that a slight product drip was emanating from the bottom outlet cap (BOC). The bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) handle appeared in the closed position. The responder observed that the product drips would ebb and then restart when the BOC filled with product. Responder then tool tightened the BOC by 1/4 turn and reset the operating handle to the closed position. Afterwards, the BOC dripping stopped. The BOC gasket was not inspected. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 1845 hrs. CST. 2/25/07. The BNSF train was then released to proceed.

column168: At 1430 on February 9, 2007 a switching crew detected a smell and saw liquid on the outside of tank car TLDX 123002 in Cotton Warehouse Yard. They were able to reseat the liquid line valve, but recommended both valves be changed before the car be moved. The incident Item #07-00643 was closed at 1822. On February 12, 2007 Rescar Inc. changed the two valves on the car, and the car was released for movement.

column168: At approximately 10:30 am on February 10, 2007 a minor release of hazardous waste onto a containment pad occurred from a sift-proof non-DOT Specification closed bulk bin.  At the time of the release, the bulk bin was being unloaded from a  roll-on/roll-off transport vehicle at a less than 10-day storage facility operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES) in Deer Park, TX.   While unloading the bin from  the roll-on/roll-off vehicle about 50 gallons of liquid material splashed over the rear gate of the bulk bin.  All of the released material was contained on a concrete pad.    Upon noticing the release, the driver stopped all operations, evacuated the area and notified his supervisor.  An in-house response crew was dispatched and arrived at the scene shortly thereafter.  They retrieved and reviewed the shipping papers and determined that the material in the bulk bin was Hazardous Waste Solid, n.o.s. (Soil contaminated with pentachlorophenol) 9, NA3077, PGIII picked up the previous day at Koppers Industries, Inc., in Tie Plant, MS.   Please note that at the time the material was loaded into the sift-proof bulk bin it was classified as being solid; however, it appears that during the course of transportation a small liquid layer formed on the top of the load.   When the bulk bin was tilted to be unloaded, the liquid layer spilled over the rear gate of the bin.    After reviewing the shipping papers, the response crew utilizing appropriate personal protection equipment and company health and safety policies and procedures entered the containment pad and commenced the clean up operations.  All of the released material was collected using appropriate absorbent materials and placed into appropriate containers for future disposal at a permitted hazardous waste disposal facility.  The cover of the bulk-bin was opened and the load was inspected for presence of any additional liquid.  It was determined that no more liquid remained in the container and it could be safely loaded onto a roll-on/roll-off vehicle for further transportation to the adjoining disposal facility.      The bulk bin was loaded and transported to the facility designated on the shipping papers without any further incidents.
column169: A representative sample of the waste material was collected and sampled by an onsite laboratory to determine if any liquid was present in the material.  An EPA test method 9095B (paint filter test) was conducted on the sample and no measurable amount of liquid was observed.  Our initial investigation concluded that the presence of liquid layer was either due to the waste material being pressed and settling during transportation and storage, or rainwater and condensate accumulating in the bulk bin.    The driver that originally picked up this container from the customer was reminded to conduct a thorough inspections of the containers at the time of the pick up to ensure that all closures are in place and that the intrusion by rainwater is prevented at all times.

column168: A BNSF YARD TAXI EMPLOYEE REPORTED THAT ADMX 30167 IN THE RAILYARD WAS LEAKING PRODUCT PROFUSELY FROM THE BOTTOM OF THIS TANK CAR. BNSF MECHANICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SITE OF ADMX 30167. BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS WERE ALSO DISPATCHED TO ASSIST IN THE MITIGATION AND REMEDIATION OF SPILLAGE. IT APPEARED THAT THE TANK SUSTAINED A CATASTROPHIC FAILURE MID-POINT BETWEEN THE TRUCK CENTERS TOWARDS THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A VERTICAL CRACK THAT WAS NOT AT A WELD LOCATION (APPROXIMATELY 18 INCHES FROM THE NEAREST WELD AND 6 INCHES FROM A PATCH). THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM ADMX 30167. CONTRACTORS DUG A TRENCH AROUND THE PERIMETER OF THE SPILL AREA, AS THE PREPONDERANCE OF THE SPILLAGE POOLED ATOP THE FROZEN GROUND, AND THIS SPILLAGE WAS VACUUMED INTO FRAC TANKS. SUMP PUMPS WERE USED TO COLLECT ANY SPILLAGE THAT HAD PENETRATED BELOW SURFACE LEVELS. THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILLAGE WAS RECOVERED AND THE REMAINDER EVAPORATED. AFTERWARDS, AIR AND GROUND MONITORING INDICATED VERY LOW ETHANOL LEVELS. RECOVERED SPILLAGE HAS BEER STAGED FOR PROFILING AND APPROPRAITE FUTURE DISPOSAL. ADMX 30167 WILL BE DIRECTED TO A DESIGNATED REPAIR FACILITY FOR FAILURE ANALYSIS AND REPAIR AFTER IT IS CLEANED AND PURGED. ADMX 30167 SPECIFICATION STENCIL NOTED TANK QUALIFICATION AS 2002 ADM-DE.

column14: AT SEA, IN TRANSIT TO MIAMI,
column168: BACKGROUND:    THE VESSEL DETECTED A STRONG SMELL FROM HOLD NO. 1 AT OR ABOUT 1600 HOURS ON FEBRUARY  2, 2007, WHILE ENROUTE TO MIAMI, FL FROM NEW ORLEANS, LA LADEN WITH CONTAINERIZED CARGO.    THE MASTER INITIATED ACTION TO PROTECT THE CREW AND VESSEL AND NOTIFIED VESSEL MANAGEMENT THE USCG.    THE USCG INSTRUCTED THE VESSEL TO REMAIN ADRIFT OFF THE ENTRANCE TO THE PORT OF  MIAMI IN WAY OF THE ROAD STEAD (ANCHORAGE) UNTIL SUCH TIME AS PROFESSIONAL ASSISTANCE COULD BE MADE AVAILABLE TO THE VESSEL FOR THE PURPOSE OF INVESTIGATING AND DETERMINING THE PROXIMATE CAUSE OF THE DOOR AND TO PRODUCE A PLAN FOR REMEDIATION OF THE PROBLEM. THIS NOTIFICATION WAS RECEIVED BY THE VESSEL AT OR ABOUT 2315 HOURS ON FEBRUARY 2.    EFFORTS WERE MADE BY THE LOCAL OFFICE OF THE VESSEL OWNER TO INITIATE A RESPONSE BY  ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE COMPANY DURING THE A.M. HOURS OF FEBRUARY 3. OUR OFFICES RE:  SPECIAL SURVEY CONTACTED AT 0900 HOURS ON FEBRUARY 3 AND REQUESTED TO ASSIST THE VESSEL ALONG WITH THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE VENTOR.    WE MET WITH THE REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE VENDOR AT THEIR OFFICES DURING THE MORNING AND REVIEWED VARIOUS DOCUMENTS SUPPLIED BY THE VESSEL OWNER REGARDING THE CARGO TN HOLD NO. 1. MOBILIZATION TOOK PLACE DURING THE EARLY AFTERNOON WHICH CONSISTED OF A 4 MEMBER RESPONSE PARTY AND LAUNCH.    THE UNDERSIGNED SURVEYOR BOARDED THE VESSEL OFFSHORE WITH THE TWO RANKINCG CBI PERSONNEL AT 1455 HOURS. THE CBI PERSONNEL WERE EQUIPPED WITH VARIOUS TEST EQUIPMENT AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPORATUS.    INVESTIGATIVE FINDINGS:    CBI PERSONNEL, PROPERLY EQUIPPED, ENTERED CARGO HOLD NO. 1 AND MADE A SITE SURVEY OF THE CONTAINERS IN-STOW WITHIN THE HOLD AS BEST POSSIBLE AT THAT TIME. THEY DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE OR WEEPAGE ON THE EXTERIOR CLADING OF TANK NO. HOTU 26 1443-4 AND THAT THIS WEEPAGE HAD DRIPPED ON CONTAINER TTNU 191585-4 OTHERWISE STOWED DIRECTLY BENEATH THE FORMER CONTAINER. A SMALL PUDDLE OF CLEAR LIQUID WAS REPORTED ON THE TANK TOP DIRECTLY UNDER THESE TWO CONTIANERS.    REVIEW OF THE DCM AND STOW PLAN RELEVANT TO HOLD No. 1 INDICATED THAT THE 20’ TANK CONTAINER IN QUESTION CONTAINED PRODUCT WITH THE FOLLOWING BASIC DESCRIPTION:    CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S. (AMINE ALKOXYLATE), CLASS 8, UN 3267     CONTAINER TTNU 191585-4 WAS DETERMINED NOT TO CONTAIN HAZMAT CARGO.    WE REVIEWED THESE FINDINGS WITH THE MASTER AND CBI PERSONNEL ON BOARD. A TENTATIVE REMEDIATION PLAN WAS DERIVED CONTINGENT UPON THE VESSEL BEING ALLOWED TO BERTH AT THE PORT OF MIAMI AND DISCHARGE CARGO SO AS TO ACCESS THE SUSPECT CARGO/CONTAINERS.

column168: THE VERTEX VEHICLE V1 WAS STOPPED IN THE SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC LANE WAITING FOR TRAFFIC TO CLEAR READY/STARTING TO MAKE A LEFT TURN INTO DESTINATION. THE FRONT TIRES OF V1 WERE TURNED LEFT AS HE WAS PREPARED TO TURN, THE ROAD THERE IS FLAT. A TRACTOR—TRAILER BEHIND V1 IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE STRUCK V1 FULL SPEED (45 MPH SPEED LIMIT) FROM THE REAR, CAUSING V1 TO MOVE DIAGONALLY ACROSS THE NORTHBOUND LANE, ROLLING V1 TO ITS SIDE ACROSS PART OF THE NORTHBOUND LANE, ROLLING V1 TO ITS SIDE ACROSS PART OF THE NORTHBOUND LANE AND THE GRAVEL DRIVE OF THE DESTINATION. V2 DRIVER SAID HE NEVER APPLIED BRAKES, WAS BLINDED BY THE SUN AND NOT FEELING WELL AND DID NOT SEE THE V1 TRUCK, NO BRAKE MARKS WERE VISIBLE ON THE STREET. AS A PRECAUTION AFTER THE CRASH, V1 DRIVER PLACED A 5-GAL. BUCKET BENEATH THE DOME ROLL—OVER/CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE TANK WHICH WAS BETWEEN THE DOME OF THE TANK AND THE GROUND, AS THE TANK WAS NOT COMPLETELY 180 DEGREES ON ITS SIDE. THIS DOME AREA WAS WET WITH ICE/RAINWATER FROM THE BUCKET, NORMALLY STOWED IN THE DOME AREA, WHICH HAD SPILLED IN THE CRASH. THE LEPC REPLACED THE BUCKET WITH A PLASTIC POOL, IN CASE THE UPRIGHTING OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED LEAKAGE. THE DOME LID WAS INTACT AND TIGHT, THE DRIVER FURTHER TIGHTENED THE DOME BOLTS AS A PRECAUTION. THE TANK WAS BADLY DAMAGED ON THE EXTERIOR FROM THE CRASH. HOWEVER IT IS A TWO-LAYER CONTAINER AND DID NOT LEAK NOR WAS THE INTERGRITY OF THE PRODUCT BREACHED IN ANY WAY. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL CONDUCTED AIR MONITORING AND 0 PPM WAS RECORDED THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE PROCESS, (ALTHOUGH THE POLICE OFFICER REPORTING THE "LEAKING" REPORTED "A STRONG ODOR"). THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT CLOSED THE HIGHWAY UNTIL THE DAMAGED VEHICLES AND RESPONSE VEHICLES WERE OUT OF THE TRAFFIC LANES. VERTEX PROVIDED A TRAILER AND PUMPED THE ENTIRE AMOUNT OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANK INTO THE TRAILER BEFORE THE DAMAGED TANK WAS UPRIGHTED, THE PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO VERTEX STOCK. NONE WAS SPILLED OR LOST IN THE TRANSFER. VERTEX LATER RETURNED AND TESTED THE GRAVEL AREA OF THE LOCATION BENEATH THE DOME, AND THE SURROUNDING AREA. A PH OF 7 WAS PRESENT THROUGHOUT THE AREA. THE POLICE AND EMERGENCY REPSONSE SUGGEST THAT A LEAK FROM TEH DOME OCCURED. VERTEX TESTED THE TRAILER AND EXAMINED AND TESTED THE SOIL AS DESCRIBED ABOVE, AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO LEAK. CONSEQUENTLY NO SPILLAGE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OCCURRED.
column169: NONE. VERTEX DOES NOT SEE A FAILURE OF ANY KIND NOR A SPILL OR IMPAIRMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: FILE-07-15 FAA        SHIPPER-CP FOODS WEST, INC.           AWB#-BUR 20325452851 OAK     ON 02/28/2006 AT 0320 PAC, A SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN THE "HAZ AREA" OF OUR RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB, LOCATED AT 17101 HEACOCK STREET, MORENO VALLEY, CA 92551. SPILL TECHNICIAN DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A STYROFOAM COOLER. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN FROZEN DINNERS BEING COOLED BY DRY ICE. THERE WAS 2 BAGS OF DRY ICE IN THE COOLER. column169: I am not trying to make excuses for what happened with this event, but sometimes we as carriers get kind of set up for failure by the way shipments are tendered to us by shippers. In this particular case the shipper tendered a single pail. As a driver you try to sneak those single container shipments into or inbetween a existing shipment already on the truck to prevent relative motion - most of the time it works but once in awhile it does not work such as this particular event. It becomes very challenging at times though with these types of shipments - maybe if there was some rule that required shippers to palletize all hazmat shipments instead of shipping them as loose containers our drivers would have a easier time and job in being able to secure them other then stuffing them inbetween other shipments.

column168: A carbon steel nipple, installed as an extension to a Dry Connect/disconnect adapter, corroded out during loading of nitric acid onto a Safeway Trailer (33375). Acid continued to pump for a couple minutes into the truck bay. All was contained in truck bay. Wind was from south and fumes dissipated in field going north. As soon a pump was cut off, fire monitor was put on fumes and vapors stopped. Probably a couple hundred gallons of acid was contained in truck bay and was neutralized in sump. At that time the truck driver was in the truck. With a south wind, he was able to exit the truck and move south toward the control room without ever entering the vapors. The driver said the Safeway truck loading nozzle had been worked on that day.    ROOT CAUSES Regulations not followed by Safeway. Wrong Metallurgy (Carbon Steel) was used in the modification of the Dry Connect/Disconnect adapter’s nozzle. This nozzle corroded out during loading of nitric acid. More over, the added extension to the dry connect/disconnect adapter made the trailer less safe because the loading nozzle assembly protruded from the crash box. Furthermore, the added extension to the dry connect/disconnect adapter was spray painted with white color which concealed it carbon steel metalurgy.
column169: 1. Discontinue usng Safeway to transport nitric acid for EDN.  2. Review the qualification process for trucking companies and consider using more      qualified personnel for this process.  3. Reaffirm in training to the Process Technicians that if they see any type      modification to a trailer, there should be accompanying paperwork certifying      that this modification was approved. Without this documentation the truck      should be turned away without loading.

column168: A conductor for the Timber Rock Railroad (TIBR) while inspecting railcars on the BNSF interchange track at Tenaha station reported a chlorine odor emanating from UTLX 82723 that was on the interchange track awaiting pick-up by the TIBR crew. The TIBR conductor and train crew immediately vacated the area and reported the odor to the local TIBR trainmaster. No injuries were incurred by the TIBR crew. The count sheriff initiated a precautionary evacuation of all residences within one mile and the Tenaha FD. Assisted in this orderly evacuation. A portion of state Highway 59 adjacent to the railyard was also closed. BNSF contract responders found the protective housing cover sealed and cut the seal to check the interior valve housing area. Responders reported finding the B-end liquid valve hissing residue product vapors. The valve was slightly open and it appeared that the valve stem was not seating properly. The responders closed the valve to full closure by 1/4 turn. Responders sprayed tie area with ammonia to test for leakage and discovered the valve stem area was still leaking. The responders then tapped on the valve stem area with a rubber mallet and retested for leakage with an ammonia spray. No further leakage was detected. Responders closed and pinned the protective housing cover; and notified the sheriff that the chlorine vapor release was stopped. The evacuation was ended at approximately 2345 hrs. CST, 2/15/07.

column168: Delta Air Lines, accepted two shipments; one from UPS Supply Chain Solution, Inc at our GSO Cargo facility, the other from DHL Global Forwarding at our ATL Cargo facility.    UPS SCS shipment was to LGW containing 3 pieces, with the total quantity of 2000 ml of UN2789, Acetic Acid, Glacial.    DHL Global Forwarding shipment was also to LGW containing 5 pieces at 5L per unit, UN 1760 Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S (Ammonium Hydroxide) and 5 pieces at 5L per unit, UN 1760 Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S (Phosporic Acid, Mixture) for a total quantity of 50L total; in addition to 1 piece of UN1950 Aerosol, Non-Flammable total quantity of 1.2 KG.    All shipments were schedule for Delta 12 / 13 February ATL – LGW.    After Delta 12 flight departure one of the 11 units from the DHL shipment was discovered at gate for the next LGW flight, with the NOTAC attached for the shipment loaded on Delta 12.  After verifying that both shipments we in-fact loaded on DAL 12 in the same compartment, exceeding the limitation of class 8 material, a requested was made for the aircraft be diverted into BOS, so the DG could be removed.
column169: This was strictly a Delta Air Lines (Delta) issue and no shipper or consignee errors were noted.  There was no release of material and no packages were compromised.    Delta has self-disclosed this incident to the FAA and is currently working with them during preparation of our corrective actions.    Delta will address our Aircraft Lead Agents (ALA) with a "Read & Sign" on proper procedures.  Newly hired ALA's will receive our Initial Compliance Training Program covering required aspects of hazardous materials transportation.  Additionally, our ALA training is being reviewed for potential updates and/or enhancements.

column168: ON 02/11/07 AT 0700 IT WAS REPORTED TO THE CHIEF DISPATCHER THAT THE CONDUCTOR ON TRAIL Q51910 WAS MAKING A PICKUP AT TYSON INDUSTRIES WHEN HE NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GAMX 9322, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA 2.2.  AT 0911 THE CONDUCTOR REPORTED SHORTNESS OF BREATH AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  EMERGENCY RESONSE CONTRACTOR, SWS, WAS DISPATCHED TO BIRMINGHAM YARD TO ISOLATED AND THE PRESSURE WAS RECORDED AT 40 PSIG WITH 24-66 PPM NEAR THE MANWAY.  THE AIR QUALITY WAS RECORDED AS 0 PPM ON THE GROUND.  VAPOR FORM THE TANK CAR WAS CRUBBED THRU 5000 GALLONS OF WATER UNTIL THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR REACHED 0 PSIG.  THE PRD WAS DISASSEMBELED AND INSPECTED.  IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE DEFECTIVE O RINGS.  THE CNAP AND O PRINGS ON THE PRD WERE REPLACED.  THE SHIPPER, TRANSAMMONIA, REQUESTED FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL TO HAVE THE CAR SENT OT A SHP FOR FINAL REPAIR AND TESTING.  THE CONDUCTOR WAS OBSERVED AND RELEASE FROM THE HOSPITAL WITH NO RESTRICITONS OR MEDICATIONS GIVEN.

column168: TRAIN Q53518, WHILE PULLING OUT OF THE YARD IN MEMPHIS, TN., DERAILED ONE HAZMAT CAR, AS WELL AS 8 MISCELLANEOUS FREIGHT CARS (NOT ATTACHED TO THE TANK CAR-FURTHER BACK IN TRAIN). THE VALVE HANDLE WAS WIRED SHUT, THE CAR WAS RERAILED, AND THE VALVE NOZZLE WAS PUT BACK INTO PALCE.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 23154 leaking from the bottom outlet area during switching activities in the railyard. GATX 23154 was carefully isolated in the railyard at the fueling tracks above track drip pans. Hazardous material responders from the Pueblo F.D. and the Transportation Technology Center (TTCI) were dispatched to mitigate the product release from GATX 23154. The F.D. responders reported finding the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) partially open with the operating rod packing gland nut (PGN) only hand tight. The responders closed the TOBOV (3/4 to one full turn) and tool tightened the operating rod’s PGN. This securement was completed by 1535 hrs. MST, 2/26/07, and the leakage from the bottom outlet cap (BOC) stopped. The F.D. responders then checked the BOC. The BOC was 1/8 turn less than tool tight. The BOC was loosened and the accumulated product inside the cap was drained into a recovery tub. With the BOC removed, no leakage from the close bottom outlet was observed. The old BOC gasket was damaged during removal and a new BOC gasket was installed. The BOC was applied and tool tightened. Response was concluded by 1520 hrs. MST, 2/26/07.

column168: A shipment the arrived via truck was inspected for Haz-mat/DGR compliance.   A plastic jerrican was found leaking at the top opening. Only a small amount ( less than 0.1L ) had leaked out. Approx 20 drums had a residue or residue remains on the exterior.  The shipment was refused for transport, marked as refused, and held in a segregated area for the FAA.    The local FAA was advised by telephone . Agent Verplank of the O'hare FAA came to our facility .   The major problem was the shipper had misclassifed the shipment. It should have been classified as NITRIC ACID UN2031 ( nitric acid was the technical name).   Single packaging is not allowed for PG II of NITRIC ACID .  The jerricans may also have been overfilled. The shipment was refused for air transport and the shipper's agent had the shipment picked up.
column169: The shipper's agent : GEOLOGISTICS in MSP , Dave 651-406-8353 fax 651-406-8355 was advised of the details and asked to have the shipper not send such shipments for air transport with this packaging/classification.   The FAA wanted to visit the shipper and asked that we not communicate directly with the shipper until the FAA visit to the shipper was done.

column168: At approx. 10:00am on Feb. 2, 2007 MWSI driver noticed a liquid leaking from the front driver’s side corner of the cargo area of his truck which was located in the receiving yard of MWSI. The driver reported the leak immediately to his supervisor. He was instructed to contain the spill with oil dry absorbent. He did so; Operations Manager was also contacted to coordinate containment and clean-up of the spilled material. It was estimated that approx. 5-10 gallons leaked in 2 areas of the MWSI property. The second area being in front (north) of the West MWSI processing building. The driver did not realize the leak when he was parked in that area as there was a lot of melting snow running off of the truck on that day, consequently the driver moved the truck to the dock/yard area where the leak was noticed. Apparently, a drum of liquid had tipped over onto its side inside the truck resulting in the spill. It was estimated by the driver that this happened as he entered the West driveway of the MWSI property as he drove over a small pile of snow while turning the corner. It was determined that the drum was not properly secured and the driver was disciplined and re-trained on proper load securement of drums. The spilled wastewater liquid contained less than 1 pound of elemental mercury. The spilled liquid and absorbent used were cleaned up by in-house properly trained personnel. The spill was completely contained on the pavement in both areas. Clean-up of the wastewater liquid included the oil dry, brooms and shovels. The duration of the spill clean-up was less than 1 hour. All residuals collected were containerized and managed properly.
column169: Additional load securement training was given to the driver of the truck involved in this spilL. Spill containment procedures were followed in applying absorbent material and driver calling his supervisor immediately.

column168: At O94Ohrs on 2-24-07, The, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that people reported product had leaked from the top of tank car GATX 74033 while being switched in the Alexandria Train Yard. He stated the railcar was located in yard 2 on track 12. Upon being notified, he advised the RMCC to make shipper notification via Chem-Trec, and conference with a Merchant. He stated a switch foreman received a misting of product in the facial area and on his fingers while the car was being moved. The switch foreman proceeded to a cleansing station to wash & rinse the affected areas, and did not require further medical attention. He also advised the tank car would be set out and isolated on track 114.   At approxirriately 1O24hrs, the Mgr.  Spoke to shipper representative an employee of Formosa Plastics USA advising him of the condition of the car. someone indicated that arrangements would be made to repair the car, and neutralize the affected areas. At ll38hrs, the Mgr. was contacted by the Childers, Louisiana Highway Patrol Hazmat Responder, who advised he was on scene. Inspection of the car by Mr. Childers revealed the #165 pound frangible disk in the safety vent assembly to be ruptured, and the splash deflector weather cap on the safety vent assembly was in the open position. Released product had dripped down the sides of the car and onto the ground.   At approximately 1141 hrs,the Mgr.  spoke to the consignee representative of the car, of Proctor & Gamble. She indicated that personnel were enroute to replace the frangible disk, and neutralize the affected areas. At 1315hrs, the Mgr. was advised by someone that the frangible disk had been replaced, and the safety vent assembly properly secured. The car and area below the car had been neutralized, making it safe fore movement. The Mgr. then contacted the Alexandria Yardmaster, and released the car for transportation without further incident.   On 3/13/07 A Manager Hazardous Materials Management received a copy of a Notice of Violation (NOV) from the Louisiana State Police, reference number H07-0024, dated 3/2/07 for this incident. Then he contacted Trooper. After researching the file, the trooper advised that the NOV was issued to UPRR in error and that a letter canceling the Nov would be forthcoming.

column168: At 1622hrs on 2-13-07, , Manager of Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Operations Manager, reported an unknown amount of product had leaked from the top of Bulktainer AWXU 630141. The container was located on chassis MOLA 251451 at the Drop Lot inside the Settegast Yard, Mile Post 377.08 of the Settegast Industrial Lead in Houston, TX. Mr. Parker advised there were no reported injuries, drains or waterways impacted Upon being notified, Mgr.  responded and requested the RMCC to make shipper notification via Chem-Trec. On arrival, Mgr.  noted a brown in color liquid on the sides of the bulktainer, and approximately 25 gallons of product spilled onto the asphalt roadway of the yard. Investigation developed that as the ramp driver was pulling the container to spot for loading. Product splashed out from the top of the container onto the ground. Inspection of the container revealed the manway cover to be closed, one of eight manway swing bolts in position, hand tight, and the remaining seven swing bolts in the down position. At approximately 17l5hrs, Mgr. spoke to the Plant Manager of Champion Technologies, of Odessa, TX, advising him of the release and condit on of the bulktainer. Arrangements were made by to have Garner Environmental respond to clean and recover the spilled product from the bulktainer and the ground. On arrival of Garner personnel, the manway was properly secured, remediation activities began, and were completed at OO47hrs on  2-1 4-07. On 2-16-07, Shipper personnel from Champion Technologies inspected, and sealed the container so that it could continue onto destination.
column169: Conduct proper post inspection of Bulktainer prior to releasing for transportation.

column168: Manager Yard Operations, reported a vapor release of an unknown substance near bowl track 18 within the Livonia Rail yard. Mr. D stated the release resembled a strong smell of ammonia. He stated there was no report of injury or evacuation efforts and no further information was available. , Manager Chemical Transportation Safety was notified and responded. At 01:24 AM, Manager R Train Operations, identified the tank car as SHPX 221200, showing to be a load of Anhydrous Ammonia. Mr. J stated the vapor was releasing from the top of the tank car. He stated there was nothing released to the ground and no waterways were affected. State Regulatory Agency notifications were issued. At 1:33 AM, advised response contractor, United States Environmental Services dispatched personnel to assist with securement of the release. At 03:15 AM, R advised the cause of the release was improper securement of the A end liquid valve to the pressure plate. He advised the release was secured at 03:35 AM by tightening alt four of the nuts on the flange at the base of the valve body

column168: On 02/27/2007 RMCC contacted CTS Mgr. M.Kelly and advised that tank car NATX37282 located in bowl track 24 in the Davidson yard was leaking from the top of the car. Upon arrival at that location Kelly observed the above car leaking out of the protective housing at a slow rate onto the top of the tankcar where it was evaporating. Upon inspection of the car Kelly found that the three inch valve on the liquid eduction line was attached less that tool tight allowing product to be released between the valve and the line. Kelly tightened the valve and the leak was stopped. After a complete inspection of the car, Kelly released it to continue onto it’s destination. Kelly made contact with the shipper of the tankcar and informed him if the problem.

column168: At 2033hrs on 2-20-07, Manager of Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Manager of Yard Operations, reported an unknown amount of product leaking from tank car ICPX 15514 at approximately Mile Post 7.11 of the Baytown Subdivision, with no reported injuries, drains, or waterways impacted. Upon being notified, responded and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec. On arrival, Mgr. Lerch noted product leakin9 from the liquid valve, and approximately 25 gallons of product on the ground. Closer inspection of the car revealed the two inch liquid valve partly open, and the liquid valve flange gasket to be worn and in poor condition. After opening the air valve, and venting car of internal vapor pressure, the leak was stopped. At approximately 2215hrs, spoke to shipper representative Business Management Leader for CL, advising him of the condition of the car. then made arrangements to have United States Environmental Services, an Environmental Contractor, respond to clean the car and neutralize the affected area. Arrangements were also made to have Rescar Mobil Railcar Repair respond to replace the failed two inch liquid valve flange gasket. On 2-21 -07 United States Environmental Services and Rescar personnel arrived on site to repair the car, and neutralize the affected areas. At  124Ohrs car ICPX 15514 was released to continue onto destination without further incident.
column169: Pressure check of car, and proper post inspection of car prior to releasing for transportation.

column168: Sloshing of the material in the tote caused the tote to fail near one of the upper corners.  The driver noticed a small amount of the material dripping from the trailer onto the left rear wheels of the trailer when he returned to his rig after stopping at the truck stop to take a break.  He immediately notified dispatch, who in turn notified the Safety Manager.  The Safety Manager contacted PSC's ER center, who dispatched Parc Environmental to the scene.  By the time Parc arrived on scene, approximately 5 gallons of the material had spilled onto the asphalt surface of the parking lot.  The balance of the material in the tote was transferred to a sound tote, which was loaded, along with the balance of the shipment, onto a second trailer and transported to the designated facility.  The acidic material on the asphalt was neutralized with calcium hydroxide, the debris placed into drums and manifested to the PSC TSD in Kent, Washington.  The trailer received a gross decontamination and was driven to the PSC TSD in Fernley, NV, where it was further decontaminated, inspected, and returned to service.
column169: Because we believe the container failure was due to deterioration of the material of construction, we now purchase new containers, rather than using reconditioned containers, for this waste stream.  In addition, we are only using the containers for one shipment.  Since incorporation these changes into our procedures we have had no incidents involving thes containers.

column168: DRIVER SHANE SHOCKEY WAS LOADING HIS SECOND LOAD OF GASOLINE THIS DAY. WHILE LOADING HE HEARD A LOUD NOISE AND IMMNEDIATELY STOPPED THE LOADING PROCESS. THE LOUD NOISE WAS THE TANK PRESSURIZING THUS EXPANDING CAUSING THE INTERAL BULK HEADS BETWEEN PUYT 4 & 5 OF THE CARGO TANK TO FAIL. THIS IN TURN CAUSED A RELEASE OF PRODUCT (GASOLINE) FROM A VENT HOLE IN AN AIR SPACE BETWEEN TWO CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AT THE BP TERMINAL BEFORE THE VENT HOLE WAS PLUGGED. 941 GALLONS WENT INTOT HE CONTAINMENT TANK. THE BALANCE OF 4022 GALLONS WAS RETURNED TO BP'S INVENTORY.    CAUSE OF THE FAILURE AFTER INVESTIGATION BY EWING OIL & BP'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS A FROZEN AIRLINE THAT OPEND THE VENT ON POT 5 ALSO THERE WAS ICE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER THAT COVERED THE SECONDARY PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE PREVENTING TI FROM OPERATING PROPERLY.
column169: EWING OIL COMPANY INC. NOW REQUIRES DRIVERS TO CHECK THE TOP OF TANKER TRAILERS DURING THE WINTER MONTHS FOR ICE. THE ICE WILL BE CLEARED BEFORE OPERATING THE VECHICLE.

column168: Plant operator took a sample of the product to be delivered.  He had opened both the internal and external valves.  After he had the sample, he closed only the external valve. He shut down the operation, removed the valve for inspection; found gasket to be in good condition; reinstalled the valve and completed unloading without further incident.
column169: We have trained our drivers to observe the sample process and to make sure plant operators have closed both valves prior to pressuring up the trailer.
